1.2 Relationships between features¶

In [27]:
from scipy.stats import spearmanr


def correlation_test(x, y):
    if x.dtype == "bool" and y.dtype == "bool":
        contingency_table = pd.crosstab(x, y)
        chi2, p, _, _ = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
        n = np.sum(contingency_table.values)  # Total number of observations
        k, r = contingency_table.shape  # Number of rows and columns
        cramers_v = np.sqrt(chi2 / (n * min(k - 1, r - 1)))
        return cramers_v, p
    elif x.dtype == "bool" and y.dtype in ["int64", "float64"]:
        return pointbiserialr(x, y)
    elif y.dtype == "bool" and x.dtype in ["int64", "float64"]:
        return pointbiserialr(y, x)
    elif x.dtype in ["int64", "float64"] and y.dtype in ["int64", "float64"]:
        return spearmanr(x, y)
    else:
        raise ValueError(
            f"Unsupported data types for correlation test: {x.dtype} and {y.dtype}"
        )


corr = pd.DataFrame(index=source_df_no_cat.columns, columns=source_df_no_cat.columns)
p_values = pd.DataFrame(
    index=source_df_no_cat.columns, columns=source_df_no_cat.columns
)

for col1 in source_df_no_cat.columns:
    for col2 in source_df_no_cat.columns:
        if col1 != col2:
            corr_value, p_value = correlation_test(
                source_df_no_cat[col1], source_df_no_cat[col2]
            )
            corr.loc[col1, col2] = corr_value
            p_values.loc[col1, col2] = p_value
        else:
            # Handle the diagonal (correlation with self)
            corr.loc[col1, col2] = 1.0
            p_values.loc[col1, col2] = 0.0

mask = np.triu(np.ones_like(corr, dtype=bool))

f, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11, 9))

cmap = sns.diverging_palette(230, 20, as_cmap=True)
corr = round(corr.applymap(pd.to_numeric), 2)

significant_mask = np.abs(corr) >= 0.025
combined_mask = mask | ~significant_mask


def format_annotation(corr_value, p_value):
    if p_value < 0.05:
        return f"{corr_value:.2f}*"
    elif abs(corr_value) > 0.3:
        return f"{corr_value:.2f}\np={p_value:.2f}"
    return ""


vectorized_formatter = np.vectorize(format_annotation)

sns.heatmap(
    corr,
    mask=combined_mask,
    cmap=cmap,
    vmax=1,
    vmin=-1,
    center=0,
    square=True,
    linewidths=0.5,
    cbar_kws={"shrink": 0.5},
    # annot=True,
    annot=vectorized_formatter(corr.to_numpy(), p_values.to_numpy()),
    fmt="",
)

plt.title("Correlation bet variable pairs")
plt.annotate(
    "* p < 0.05\nonly columns where correlation is > 0.025 shown (",
    xy=(0.5, -0.175),
    xycoords="axes fraction",
    xytext=(0, -40),
    textcoords="offset points",
    ha="center",
    va="top",
)

Because the datatypes of features vary we had to use different methods to measure the strength and significance of each pair:

  • Chi-Squared Test: Assesses independence between two categorical variables. For bool-bool pairs due to categorical nature.
  • Point Biserial Correlation: Measures correlation between a binary and a continuous variable. For bool-numerical pairs to account for mixed data types.
  • Spearman's Rank Correlation: Assesses monotonic relationship between two continuous variables. Used for numerical-numerical pairs (for non-normally distributed data).

Because the Chi-Squared test outputs an unbound statistic/value which can't be directly compared to pointbiserialr or Spearman Rank we have converted them to a Cramér's V: value which is normalized between 0 and 1. This was done to make the values in the matrix more uniform however we must note that Cramér's V and Spearman's correlation coefficients are fundamentally different statistics and generally can't be directly compared.

Results:¶

Generally the correlation matrix provides no particularly unexpected insights:

as might be expected there is significant positive correlation between annual income and:

  • Being a frequent flyer
  • Travelling Abroad
  • Buying travel insurance

All of these variables are only correlated with each other, this is an example of multivariate correlation since these variables are confounding:

wealthier people travel more -> they are more likely to buy travel insurance.

Additionally older people are more likely to buy insurance than young people but the corelation is not particularly strong.

This is pretty expected and people like are this generally the main target market for consumers.

Identifying people who do not have high annual income but might be likely to travel and thus buy insurance might be a lot harder.

One not intuitively obvious observation is that in this specific dataset government workers tend to have lower incomes than those in the private sector.

1.3 Testing Hypothesis¶

We have formulated several hypothesis based on the previous observations (this exactly the same approach that was used when building the correlation matrix):

In [29]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency, ttest_ind
from IPython.display import Markdown, display

# Hypothesis 1: Chi-square test
contingency_table = pd.crosstab(
    source_df_no_cat["Government_Sector"], source_df_no_cat["TravelInsurance"]
)
chi2, p_chi, dof, expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)

display(
    Markdown(
        f"""
    ### Hypothesis 1: Government Sector Employment and Travel Insurance Purchase
    - **Hypothesis**: Government sector employees are less likely to buy travel insurance.
    - **Null Hypothesis**: Being a government sector employee has no effect on purchasing travel insurance.
    - **Chi-square test p-value**: {p_chi:.2f}
    {'- **Result**: Reject the null hypothesis. Significant relationship.' if p_chi < 0.05 else '- **Result**: Fail to reject the null hypothesis. No significant relationship.'}
"""
    )
)

### Hypothesis 1: Government Sector Employment and Travel Insurance Purchase
- **Hypothesis**: Government sector employees are less likely to buy travel insurance.
- **Null Hypothesis**: Being a government sector employee has no effect on purchasing travel insurance.
- **Chi-square test p-value**: 0.00
- **Result**: Reject the null hypothesis. Significant relationship.

(not that since we're testing the relationship between two categorical/binary variables there is no directionality)

In [30]:
# Hypothesis 2: Independent Samples t-test
gov_sector = source_df_no_cat[source_df_no_cat["Government_Sector"] == True][
    "AnnualIncome"
]
non_gov_sector = source_df_no_cat[source_df_no_cat["Government_Sector"] == False][
    "AnnualIncome"
]
t_stat, p_ttest = ttest_ind(gov_sector, non_gov_sector)

display(
    Markdown(
        f"""
    
    ### Hypothesis 2: Government Sector Employment and Annual Income
    - **Hypothesis**: Government sector employees have a lower annual income.
    - **Null Hypothesis**: Being a government sector employee does not affect annual income.
    - **Independent Samples t-test p-value**: {p_ttest:.2f}
    {'- **Result**: Reject the null hypothesis. Significant difference in income.' if p_ttest < 0.05 else '- **Result**: Fail to reject the null hypothesis. No significant difference in income.'}
    """
    )
)

### Hypothesis 2: Government Sector Employment and Annual Income
- **Hypothesis**: Government sector employees have a lower annual income.
- **Null Hypothesis**: Being a government sector employee does not affect annual income.
- **Independent Samples t-test p-value**: 0.00
- **Result**: Reject the null hypothesis. Significant difference in income.

i.e. government workers (in this dataset not neccesarily in general) tend to have significantly lower income than private sector workers.

  • government workers are more "risk averse" and are more likely to buy insurance when they do travel (or other explanations might be valid too).
  • domestic travellers might also buy travel insurance.

1.5 PCA¶

We have attempted to use PCA to reduce the dimensionality of the dataset.

This might be necessary for datasets which include very high numbers of features. Since this specific dataset is very simple and includes a very low number of columns this was only done for informative/educational purposes.

Additionally, we have included binary/categorical variables which also is generally not advisable in real world cases.

Interestingly all the models (besides the overall worst performing model, Logistic with PCA) struggle at identifying the users who are likely to buy insurance:

  • Almost all clients who are unlikely to buy insurance (90-98%) are identified correctly
  • HOWEVER: a significant proportion of those who have bought insurance are misclassified

Considering our goal there performance of our models is very poor because 40-60% of potential clients can't be identified.

Annual income seems to be the best indicator of whether a person would buy travel insurance.

Conclusion¶

  • We have tried multiple different ML models to predict the insurance columns
  • While the overall performance is reasonable good (F1 > 0.8) the model underestimates the TravelInsurance = True class
    • This is a big issue for our client because we can only identify around 60% of all potential clients.
    • On the positive our model is very good at identifying people who don't need travel insurance (almost 95% in the best case) which means that we can only contact the people who are likely to buy it which results in very high efficiency of our sales team.
